title: Bell Real Estate Cycling Training Camp
USA Cycling Beginning Racer Program
description:
USA Cycling Beginning Racer Program

Clinics are:
Saturday, January 10, 2015, Cat 5 Men and Cat 4 Women
Saturday, January 17, 2015, Cat 5 Men and Cat 4 Women
Saturday, February 21, 2014, Cat 5 Men

Please register BELOW.

After the success of the first two USA Cycling Beginner Racing Program (BRP) clinics in 2014, Gary Tingley has added another 3 clinics in 2015.

Registration is $30. Clinic limited to fifty (50) cyclists (over the age of 16). The clinics are in San Diego at the Mira Mesa Huennekens course.
course:
What Is USAC BRP?

USAC BRP is open to Men Category 5 licensed racers and Women Category 4 licensed racers over the age of 16, and is designed to develop a rider’s bike racing skills, allowing for safer and more enjoyable racing experiences. Riders who complete both the clinic and race portion will earn upgrade points, or have the events count as mass finishes. For a Men Category 5 racers and Women Category 4 racers, one (1) clinic completion counts as two (2) mass start finishes. This program was developed and modeled after the Northern California Early Bird Racing Series, directed by Larry Nolan, Laurel Green, Matt McNamara, John Cheetham, and Dan Smith.

Men Category 5 cyclists may upgrade to Category 4 by obtaining ten (10) points (race days). Women Category 4 cyclists may upgrade to Category 3 by obtaining ten (10) points (race days). These points can be achieved by finishing 10 mass start races, or by completing five (5) USAC approved BRP clinics, or a combination of both. Mass start races count as one (1) point for each completed race and USAC approved BRP clinics count as two (2) points for each clinic.
registration:
Details and location specifics will be emailed to registrants one week prior to each clinic.

Each Clinic Includes
*On and off the bike training with USA Cycling Level 1 coaches and mentors
*30-minute training practice race
*Link to handouts on workouts and skills practices

Show up prepared with cycling clothing, bicycle, helmet, and any other items you need for riding your bike. Bring your own water and snack. This clinic is a participation based clinic, so being ready to ride is important to get the maximum out of your participation.

Agenda

8:45am: Check in
9:00am: Introduction and Safety
9:15am: Begin instruction
10:30am: Training Practice Race
11:15am: Post-Training Race Debrief, Q&A and Wrap Up
12:00noon: Clinic complete

All participants must be USAC licensed, sign a release form, and wear a helmet.

Questions? Contact Gary Tingley (garytingley@gmail.com) or Robert Panzera (robert@ccsd.com).

title: USA Cycling Beginning Race Program(BRP) p/b Rock N' Road
description:
USA Cycling Beginning Racer Program

Clinic are on Thursdays , April 9th, April 23rd, May 7th, May 21st and June 4th..
Please register BELOW.


After the success of criterium racing clinics in January, March, and August of 2014, Gary Tingley has moved the bar by producing and directing a Beginning Racing Program (BRP) under the guidance of USA Cycling (USAC) during the fall 2014 and winter 2015.

Registration is $30. Clinic limited to fifty (30) Category 5 cyclists (over the age of 16). The Clinics will be at the Orange County Great Park in Irvine, CA, the same location of the Grand Prix @ the Great Park is located. 

What Is USAC BRP?

USAC BRP is open to Category 5 men and Category 4 women licensed racers over the age of 16, and is designed to develop a rider’s bike racing skills, allowing for safer and more enjoyable racing experiences. Riders who complete both the clinic and race portion will earn upgrade points, or have the events count as mass finishes. For a Category 5 men racers and Category 4 women, one (1) clinic completion counts as two (2) mass start finishes. This program was developed and modeled after the Northern California Early Bird Racing Series, directed by Larry Nolan, Laurel Green, Matt McNamara, John Cheetham, and Dan Smith.

Category 5 cyclists may upgrade to Category 4 by obtaining ten (10) points (race days). These points can be achieved by finishing 10 mass start races, or by completing five (5) USAC approved BRP clinics, or a combination of both. Mass start races count as one (1) point for each completed race and USAC approved BRP clinics count as two (2) points for each clinic.

Clinics are directed by Gary Tingley, M.S.,, USAC Level 1 Cycling Coach.
course: The course will be on the runways of the old El Toro Air Station now know as the Orange County Great Park
registration: Please pre-register online at www.usacycling.org
notes:
Each Clinic Includes
On and off the bike training with USA Cycling Level 1 coaches and mentors
30-minute training practice race
Five (5) take-home training workouts and handouts
Additional skills and sprinting workouts via Trainingpeaks™ (code will be provided)
Show up prepared with cycling clothing, bicycle, helmet, and any other items you need for riding your bike. Bring your own water and snack. This clinic is a participation based clinic, so being ready to ride is important to get the maximum out of your participation.

Clinic agenda (day of the clinic)
4:30pm sign in opens for BRP participants
4:55pm riders stage at BRP area (course will be closed area, short loop for practicing drills)
5:00pm start clinic, pre-brief/intros, instruction
5:45pm instruction concludes 15 minutes prior to race to prep for race
6:00pm 40min Men's/ Women's  Cat 4/5 race begins
6:45pm race ends
6:50pm Q&A session/debrief
7:00pm clinic concludes

Clinic breakdown

Basic Pack Skills – Protecting Your Front Wheel
Cornering – Choosing and Holding Your Line
Pack Awareness & Skills
Sprinting Basics
Bringing it All Together
All participants must be USAC licensed, sign a release form, and wear a helmet.

52nd Mt. Tamalpais Hill Climb
description:
The Mt. Tam Hill Climb is one of the oldest bike races in the west, and this year will be the 52nd running. The race starts in Stinson Beach, with four flat miles along Bolinas Lagoon. Then the climbing starts - a twisting climb up Bolinas-Fairfax road, followed by the rolling climb up the "seven sisters" on Ridgecrest. As a hill climb, it's a great "first race" for new racers.

All racers will get some great schwag with their entry, courtesy of our sponsors - an event water bottle from Bespoke Cycles, cycling socks by Ornot, and banana bread by Jane on Fillmore at the finish line.
course: Race starts at the exit of Stinson Beach Park, heads north up Highway 1, right on Bolinas-Fairfax Road, right on Ridgecrest, finishing at the Rock Spring parking lot on the West Peak of Mt. Tam. About 12 miles and 2,000' of climbing.
registration: On-site registration will open at 7:30, and close 20 minutes before each race. Online registration available until September 9. Discounted race fee for early registration.
notes:
We've been asked to keep Stinson Beach town as clear as possible and for that reason, marshals will direct you to warm up by heading north on Highway 1 until 10 minutes before the first race start - after that the starting area will be tied up with race staging and you won't be able to exit. You may want to bring a trainer or rollers to warm up in the parking lot.

After the finish, please descend to Stinson where we'll post all results by approximately noon. Officials will not post any results at the finish line. If you stay in the Rock Spring area, stay off the road and follow marshals' instructions - it's essential that we keep Ridgecrest and the intersection clear.

The Public field is a Cat 5 field by USA Cycling rules, but it's intended for those looking for a less intense event. If you have an annual Cat 5 license, you should sign up for one of the other Cat 5 fields.
directions: In the town of Stinson Beach, the park is just north of the main intersection (the one with the stop signs). Turn into the park and follow marshal directions to event parking - we only have use of some of the park.
